As already mentioned before, the Process Designer can execute processes by calling an external Process Engine for testing and debugging purposes. Before a process can be executed, some configuration tasks have to be completed.

## Process Engine
Executing a process requires a Process Engine to be configured for use with the Designer.

This configuration can be set up in the preferences. How to do this is explained in [Process Engine](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-user-guide-preferences-1#process-engine). If the configured Engine is managed (local) it also needs to be started, by selecting it in the *Select Process Engine* combo box in the toolbar and clicking the *Start Engine* toolbar button. Once a running Process Engine is selected, the *Start Engine* button is replaced by *Stop Engine*, the palette in the editor is populated with the activity modules from this Engine and the Designer is ready for executing processes.

*Technical Detail*

> Note

Internally Process Designer has two ways of executing a process, a synchronous and an asynchronous way. Which one it uses depends on whether or not a message queue is set for the Process Engine configuration used for execution. This detail is hidden from the user because it does not affect the way of using executions.

If no message queue is configured the execution will be done synchronously, meaning that in the background, Process Designer waits for the process to to finish. This has certain drawbacks, for example if the connection to the Process Engine is interrupted during execution, Process Designer can not track the progress of the process any more. Especially for long running processes this is not optimal.

If a message queue is configured and the Process Engine uses message logging, the process is executed asynchronously. This means that Process Designer subscribes to a message topic where it expects the Process Engine to publish its log messages. Whenever it receives a log message belonging to one of its process executions, this execution is updated. This method is more robust, especially for long running processes and should be used if message logging is available.

## Launch Configurations
Before a process can be launched, a launch configuration has to be created. A launch configuration contains all the information required for starting a process. If the active process has not been executed in the current session of the Process Designer yet, clicking on the *Execute Process* menu entry or toolbar button will open the *Launch Configurations* dialog and automatically create a launch configuration for this process. The dialog can also be opened via the *Launch Configurations* entry in the menu or the dropdown next to the *Execute Process *button in the toolbar.

The left side of the *Launch Configurations* dialog lists all available launch configurations grouped by the process definition they belong to. Entries for all process definitions which are currently open in the editor are automatically added to the list. For the currently active process, a launch configuration is automatically selected, if there are none yet, a new configuration is created. At the top of the list there is an entry *remote* which can be used to create launch configurations without a local process definition file. For the existing processes in the list (or the *remote* entry), launch configurations can be created or removed with the *Add* and *Delete* buttons in the toolbar above or in the context menu. Via toolbar or context menu launch configurations can also be copied and pasted as well as export to and imported from files.

When a launch configuration is selected in the list, the right side of the dialog shows the configuration information. At the top there is a text field for the launch configuration name.

This name only serves for identification by users, it has no influence on the actual execution. The area below the name is separated into seven tabs, containing different parts of the launch configuration. These tabs are described in the sub-sections below.

The *OK* button of the dialog applies all changes and closes the dialog without starting a process. The *Apply* button applies all changes and leaves the dialog open. The *Launch* button applies all changes, closes the dialog and starts a process execution using the launch configuration selected in the list. The *Cancel* button closes the dialog and discards all changes.

### Overview
This tab provides a read-only summary of the most important information contained in the launch configuration.

### Parameters
In this tab users can define parameters to pass when starting the process. If the Start Element of the process has mappings with variables as source, the list on the left side will be pre-filled with placeholder parameters for these variables. The names of the variables are shown in grey. Placeholders can be turned into actual parameters by double clicking on the name in the list or by selecting it and changing it on the right side. Additional parameters can be added by clicking on the *Add* button and changing the name in the list. Parameters can be deleted using the *Delete* button. When a parameter which has been created from a placeholder is deleted, the placeholder appears in the list again instead.

When a parameter is selected in the list, the right side shows the content for this parameter. At the top, a type can be defined. This field is optional and the parameter will be provided as text if no type is set. Otherwise the provided values will be converted to the defined type on the client side before they are sent to the Process Engine. The *Prompt* checkbox can be checked if the User wants an additional prompt dialog for providing values for this parameter to appear each time the launch configuration is executed. If this prompt is set, the values below can either be left empty, so they need to be provided through the prompt later or values can be defined as defaults which may be overwritten by the prompt. If the prompt is active, an optional label shown in the prompt dialog can be defined. Below the prompt there is a list of values to set for this parameter. Each value has an input field similar to the one for Mapping Sources in the Property Sheet (see [Mappings](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-properties#mappings)). The Icon in front can be clicked to switch between using literal or a URL as source. If the source is literal, the text put into the field will be used as the value directly. Otherwise, the content of the field will be interpreted as a URL. When the execution is launched, the the URL is read on the client side and its content used as value for the parameter. The button with the three dots at the end of the field has a different behaviour depending on the source type. For a literal it opens a dialog with a larger text field, for a URL it opens a resource explorer dialog for opening a file. Multiple values for a parameter can be provided by filling multiple input fields. A new input field for an additional value appears as soon as the last one is filled in. Values can be deleted by removing the content of the field or by clicking on the icon in front and selecting *Delete*.

The *Parameters* tab can also be used to define instance constants which are set when the process is started. At the bottom of the parameter list, the list can be switched from variables to constants. Defining parameters for instance constants works just like for variables, the only difference is that there are no pre-filled placeholders.

### Details
This tab contains some basic information about the launch configuration:

**Process File**

This field shows the local process definition file this launch configuration belongs to. The value corresponds to the process entry in the list of launch configurations on the left side of the dialog, so if it changes if it changes, the launch configuration will also be assigned to a different process entry in the list. If the field is empty, the launch configuration is assigned to the remote entry. Using the button at the end of the line, the value of the field can be changed, either by editing it manually, selecting a process definition file in a Resource Explorer dialog or by selecting an existing process entry from the launch configuration list.

**URL**

Defines the process URL which should be provided when starting a process. If the launch configuration does not stream the process definition (can be configured in the checkbox below), this URL is used by the Process Engine to load the process definition on the server side. By default a new launch configuration has {file} as the URL value. This means that upon execution, the location of the local process definition file will be used as URL. If the process is streamed or the Process Engine which executes it has access to the same process definition file, this default value can be used, otherwise an actual URL of a process definition file available to the Process Engine must be specified.

**Stream**

Specifies whether the process definition should be streamed to the Process Engine from the client or loaded on the server-side from the provided URL. A launch configuration must be assigned to a currently open process or a locally available process file for it to be streamed. If the process definition is open it will be streamed directly from memory, otherwise Process Designer reads the file first.

**Thread Pool**

Sets the thread pool parameter when instantiating the process, deciding in which thread pool the instance will be executed.

**Auto Dispose**

Sets the autoDispose parameter when instantiating the process, overriding the default value for autoDispose configured in the Process Engine. If the value is empty, the parameter will not be set and the server default is used, otherwise the parameter will be set to the selected value. This option can be especially useful when the autoDispose setting in the Process Engine is set to something other than never or fetch. In that case it can happen that the process instance is disposed before Process Designer has received the final instance snapshot, leading to the execution appearing as stuck in a previous state and cant be refreshed anymore. This can be solved by setting the autoDispose parameter in the launch configuration to fetch, so the Process Engine will wait for Process Designer to retrieve the final snapshot before deleting the instance.

### Credentials
This tab can be used to provide credentials for a user under which the process should be executed. If the Process Engine configuration which is used specifies credentials as well, those are overwritten by the launch configuration credentials.

In order to specify credentials, an authentication type must be selected. This can be done manually, by choosing one of the options from the drop down menu. If a valid URL has been provided, the *Detect* button to the right of the drop down can be used to automatically find out what kind of authentication the server requests. The area below is dynamically filled with input fields specific to the authentication type when the selection changes. Some types have advanced fields, which are only visible when the *Advanced* check box is checked.

### Log
In this tab users can specify custom logging behaviour for the process execution. These values overwrite the log settings of the Process Engine.

- *Trace Log* check box: Enable or disable trace logging.

- *Diagnostic Level* combo box: Set the log level for diagnostic logging.

- *Data Level* combo box: Set the log level for data logging.

### Attributes
This tab can be used to specify attributes which are set on the process instance after instantiation. The attributes are listed in the table and can be modified by clicking on a cell. Add and remove attributes using the *Add* and *Delete* buttons.

### Metadata
This tab can be used to specify metadata for the launch configuration. This metada can be used to provide additional information to users, but has no effect during execution. The metadata fields are listed in the table and can be modified by clicking on a cell. Add and remove attributes using the *Add* and *Delete* buttons.

When a new launch configuration is created, Process Designer automatically fills in some default metadata fields. The metadata field called *name* is equivalent to the launch configuration name specified in the text field above. The *description* field is empty by default and can be used to provide a meaningful description for users. The *created* and *created-by *fields are populated with the timestamp and user name once at creation and can be changed. The *last modified* field contains a timestamp set each time the launch configuration is changed, manual changes will be overwritten.

## Execute Process
Once a valid launch configuration is available for a process, it can be executed. Process execution is not restricted to open processes, any launch configuration for any existing process can be started. A process can be launched via the *Launch* button in the *Launch Configuration* dialog. Previously used launch configurations for the active process can be started again using the *Execute Process* toolbar button. The button itself starts the last used launch configuration again, the dropdown menu next to it lists the last five launch configurations used.

If at least one of the parameters of a launch configuration is configured to have a prompt, an additional dialog containing the parameter prompts will open upon execution. The prompt dialog provides a field for defining input values for one parameter at a time. The text at the top center shows the name of the current variable. If there are more parameters with prompts, there is a forward button to the right of the name which selects the next one. A back button for returning to a previous parameter appears on the left side once the forward button has been clicked. Below the line with the name and the buttons there is a text containing either the label of the prompt if one has been set in the launch configuration definition or a default label. Below the label there is an area containing the value input fields. Those fields work exactly the same way as the ones for the general parameters defined in the launch configuration dialog, as described in [Parameters.](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-user-guide-process-execution-1#parameters) If the parameter already has dafault values, those will be pre-filled and can be altered freely. Once the parameters have been filled in, the excution can be started with the *Launch* button or aborted with the *Cancel* button.

As soon as a launch configuration is started, the new execution will be added to the bottom of the list in the *Process Execution List* view. The *Start Time* column shows the time the process was launched, the *Process Execution* column shows the process name and launch configuration used, the *Engine* column shwos the name of the engine configuration used and the *Status* column shows the current state the process is in. A process can be terminated and killed, using the button *Terminate*, which changes to *kill* after termination. The process and all associated information will be kept in the list after the process is finished, failed or terminated. To remove an execution use the buttons *Remove* and *Remove All*. Note that removing a process execution from the list does not mean that the process will be removed from the Process Engine, it only removes the association between the process execution and the Designer. In case the synchronization between Process Designer and Process Engine doesnt work properly, the *Refresh* button can be used to update the status of the execution. When selecting the execution in the list, the *Properties*, *Log* and *Pipeline* views will show additional information regarding this execution. For more information about these views see the subsections in [Views](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-user-guide-views-1).
